709158f-a.text:
ONE OF THE FRONTS OF THE AMERICAN WING OF THE METROPOLITAN MUSEUM OF ART IN NEW YORK
This facade is a replacement,stone by stone, of the front of the old United States Assay Building on Wall Street, recently torn down, and originally built in 1824

The south facade of the American Wing. Formerly the facade of the U.S. Branch Bank, and later of the U.S. Assay Office, at 15 Wall Street. It was built about 182-24 by a well-known New York architect, W.S. Thompson. Torn down in 1914, the stones numbered and stored, and re-erected at the museum.
February 1925

718496f-b.title: Manhattan: Central Park West - 80th Street
718496f-b.text:
(1) Central Park West, showing the West Side from about 80th to 82nd Streets. Although not clearly shown in this picture there is a clearing from 81st to 82nd Streets, where the old Beresford Apartment House has been demolished to make way for a new building.
October 20th, 1928
P. L. Sperr.

(2) The same, from a closer view taken seven weeks earlier, before the leaves began to fall,and showing the Beresford in the last stages of demolition.
P. L. Sperr.
September 9th,1928.
